00:33:03.021 --> 00:33:08.971
Not enough demand for it, Mother, not enough people
want it. So they don’t produce too much of it anymore.

00:33:09.004 --> 00:33:11.001
What is that?

00:33:11.014 --> 00:33:17.361
The... you know, aesthetic, [unclear] things like
that. The average person simply can’t afford it.

00:33:17.407 --> 00:33:19.907
But what is that they produce actually?

00:33:19.929 --> 00:33:24.970
OK, although they do produce a lot of things [but
I think], they do heavy machinery production.

00:33:24.970 --> 00:33:31.890
And there’s, there’s not much that goes into the
household items, so much imported, that is in plastic.

00:33:31.944 --> 00:33:35.220
But not on these finer things, I think.

00:33:35.219 --> 00:33:37.719
(unclear)

00:33:54.913 --> 00:33:59.410
Only in Toledo I found they were
making beautiful glass things,

00:33:59.410 --> 00:34:05.040
beautiful bells of glass and all
that, hand things, hand-made, Toledo.

00:34:05.041 --> 00:34:09.240
Tiffan was the name of the place
where I went. It’s a village like...

00:34:09.240 --> 00:34:09.968
Murano.

00:34:09.968 --> 00:34:14.086
And I was really surprised how
they were moulding into things

00:34:14.086 --> 00:34:17.768
and beautiful things they
were making out of glass.

00:34:17.779 --> 00:34:19.869
Very nice.

00:34:19.888 --> 00:34:23.849
Like bangles not there, but
something like this kind.

00:34:29.169 --> 00:34:36.757
So there must have been lots of things of that kind here, because industrial development took much late, isn’t it?

00:34:36.767 --> 00:34:40.409
It came much later in life.

00:34:40.417 --> 00:34:48.647
So they must have lived with, you see, some
sort of plates and things must have had.

00:34:59.574 --> 00:35:02.074
Oven thing.

00:35:06.086 --> 00:35:08.586
But that, too, was made in Poland.

00:35:08.586 --> 00:35:11.086
I’ll try next time.

00:35:12.526 --> 00:35:16.059
It’s like, you know, you want to
see something made in America.

00:35:16.059 --> 00:35:18.019
You don’t find anything.

00:35:19.459 --> 00:35:25.109
But if we are looking then in the assembly line which
is, was the, the exploiter of the mass production.

00:35:25.135 --> 00:35:28.769
So we moved away from the er what
we would call cottage industry.

00:35:28.778 --> 00:35:34.038
No, but sort of, we want to have,
say, something made in here.

00:35:35.667 --> 00:35:38.167
Eh? What she’s saying?

00:35:38.167 --> 00:35:40.048
They make blue jeans.

00:35:40.048 --> 00:35:42.548
They make blue jeans here.

00:35:43.058 --> 00:35:45.558
Blue jeans.

00:35:47.299 --> 00:35:49.018
The American hand-made things.

00:35:49.018 --> 00:35:50.569
Blue jeans?

00:35:50.599 --> 00:35:52.139
The Americans have no taste.

00:35:52.139 --> 00:35:53.439
Americans what?

00:35:53.459 --> 00:35:54.789
They have no taste.

00:35:54.822 --> 00:35:58.159
I think they are the greatest,
that's why you are all existing.

00:36:03.684 --> 00:36:08.036
They buy from all over the world. You
don’t know, you get Chinese goods here.

00:36:08.070 --> 00:36:12.626
Every sort of good you can get in America
where you cannot find it anywhere.

00:36:12.628 --> 00:36:17.968
All the best things there. I've even bought
all the old things from all over the world.

00:36:18.001 --> 00:36:20.268
I mean, they have a good taste, no doubt.

00:36:20.288 --> 00:36:23.448
They are the ones who got
the sense of antiques also.

00:36:23.448 --> 00:36:25.948
They are the ones who introduced
this idea of antique.

00:36:25.948 --> 00:36:31.332
I wouldn’t say that, but what I am
saying that there should be something.

00:36:31.360 --> 00:36:34.442
Why I am asking you this question is this:

00:36:35.870 --> 00:36:38.370
everything I say has something behind it.

00:36:41.757 --> 00:36:46.517
Now you tell Me why. Let’s see how
far you understand Your Mother.

00:36:46.517 --> 00:36:51.031
Course we should be, we should be doing
something. We should be making handicrafts.

00:36:51.045 --> 00:36:52.311
What is needed…

00:36:52.311 --> 00:36:53.861
No, no.

00:36:53.870 --> 00:36:55.361
To create the beauty.

00:36:55.381 --> 00:36:57.461
Not that. No, no.

00:36:59.901 --> 00:37:02.562
Some sort of enterprise that
Sahaja Yogis can do together? So

00:37:03.962 --> 00:37:05.091
You are very near.

00:37:07.372 --> 00:37:10.362
You see, why I am saying so…

00:37:10.362 --> 00:37:13.272
First I was thinking that we’ll come to America.

00:37:13.272 --> 00:37:17.832
We’ll propagate; it will work out
very well, Sahaja Yoga, this, that.

00:37:17.832 --> 00:37:22.332
But I found the people, you see, they get realisation;
then they are finished. They are no more there.

00:37:22.347 --> 00:37:26.514
They do not take it that seriously.
They become frivolous or thing.

00:37:26.514 --> 00:37:30.027
So how to settle them down? Because
the environment is very bad;

00:37:30.027 --> 00:37:35.260
environment is so bad that everything fizzles
out, you see; everything sort of fritters away.

00:37:35.267 --> 00:37:38.457
Everything. I mean, the
seriousness of it goes away.

00:37:38.457 --> 00:37:43.627
People just try to play with Sahaja Yoga, little
bit here and there. They don’t take it seriously.

00:37:43.631 --> 00:37:47.015
So I thought of a plan which
I’ve told you before also,

00:37:47.044 --> 00:37:55.442
that in a big land in India, I was thinking of
starting a school for teaching them Indian crafts.

00:37:57.982 --> 00:38:02.652
And that for that, whatever you are
not making here, we can make there.

00:38:02.652 --> 00:38:06.269
But now I find that you are making nothing. So…

00:38:11.482 --> 00:38:19.232
So I was thinking of inviting people
from America to come down there,

00:38:19.232 --> 00:38:22.522
settle down there for three months
and learn a particular craft.

00:38:22.534 --> 00:38:25.034
We can have about twenty-one
crafts I've found out,

00:38:25.034 --> 00:38:33.134
which are very, absolutely very, very Indian crafts and old crafts, and they can be taught very easily.

00:38:33.166 --> 00:38:35.233
Within three months you can pick up the craft.

00:38:35.233 --> 00:38:40.233
But by that, learning by that, you
won’t be able to do it yourself

00:38:40.276 --> 00:38:43.715
because it’s a, it’s, er,
labour, it’s very expensive here.

00:38:43.745 --> 00:38:47.775
But what you can do is that,
supposing you like something,

00:38:47.807 --> 00:38:52.395
and now you have, now for
example this piece of silk.

00:38:52.411 --> 00:38:57.441
Now to get it in the market it’s
easy that you go and get it.

00:38:57.451 --> 00:39:05.967
But supposing you know the craft, then you can precisely say what sort of a thing you would like to have to sell it.

00:39:05.986 --> 00:39:09.154
So you might have something
very unique things to suggest.

00:39:09.154 --> 00:39:12.676
Because Indians whatever they will
send you whatever they have.

00:39:12.679 --> 00:39:17.756
But your style, what you want
to have or what is you like,

00:39:17.781 --> 00:39:22.796
whatever you will be using that only
if you know the craft you can... Yes.

00:39:22.826 --> 00:39:25.852
Mother, Radha was having an idea,

00:39:25.866 --> 00:39:33.712
because there is good leather in India which
is imported in form of raw material [unclear].

00:39:33.723 --> 00:39:40.567
Theoretically, tradition of leather was here in this country, and there’s definitely a market for it also.

00:39:40.564 --> 00:39:43.757
That is just an idea.

00:39:43.767 --> 00:39:46.267
I mean, you want to export.

00:39:47.827 --> 00:39:51.987
You see, all such handmade things from
here cannot fetch you much money,

00:39:51.987 --> 00:39:54.787
because the reason is, it is very expensive.

00:39:54.804 --> 00:39:58.544
But you can get it, cheaper things
from other countries, like Taiwan,

00:39:58.544 --> 00:40:01.044
this, that, is sending to you, but cheapish stuff.

00:40:01.044 --> 00:40:03.814
But from India you can get genuine, good things.

00:40:03.814 --> 00:40:06.014
That’s what I am talking about.

00:40:06.014 --> 00:40:07.034
Leather work.

00:40:07.034 --> 00:40:16.894
Leather work from India, made in USA. For the
American market. That’s what I am talking about.

00:40:16.894 --> 00:40:22.022
But that is the taste part of it you
can tell us if you know the craft,

00:40:22.950 --> 00:40:23.592
isn’t it?

00:40:23.592 --> 00:40:30.332
If you don’t know the craft little bit, at least, you
won’t be able to exactly say or design it and say.

00:40:30.332 --> 00:40:34.742
Another thing says, Indian furniture or
something, it’s quite good, hand-made.

00:40:34.789 --> 00:40:40.858
Now if we send you the parts of the furniture,
if you know the craft, you can assemble it.

00:40:40.882 --> 00:40:43.382
it would be much cheaper to send it here.

00:40:43.382 --> 00:40:46.542
(short break)

00:40:46.590 --> 00:40:51.388
country, which you can first of all what I
would suggest that you must learn the craft,

00:40:51.398 --> 00:40:57.488
little bit, to understand what can be done.
Supposing now this is the thing in pieces.

00:40:57.488 --> 00:41:04.698
Now you should know in this what we can do,
how far can we go, what colours we can use.

00:41:04.714 --> 00:41:09.254
And then you exactly tell that
this is what we have to do.

00:41:09.258 --> 00:41:11.758
Then the people can do it.
Then you can sell them here.

00:41:11.758 --> 00:41:17.833
But Sahaja Yoga should never be
involved with any, any business.

00:41:17.863 --> 00:41:22.743
I hope it is clear. No business should
be done under the name of Sahaja Yoga.

00:41:22.743 --> 00:41:29.562
Hah, you can have your own cooperative
or anything between yourselves,

00:41:29.572 --> 00:41:36.773
but never, never use Sahaja Yoga, the
name, My name or anything for any business.

00:41:36.783 --> 00:41:39.893
Sahaja Yoga is doing no business at all.

00:41:39.893 --> 00:41:50.973
But by this kind of a thing, we’ll generate a better taste,
better aesthetics, better living standards in this country.

00:41:50.983 --> 00:41:55.161
So I would suggest that when
we start this programme,

00:41:57.463 --> 00:42:03.511
I have to also get one more “Yes”
from you, because you are Americans.

00:42:03.511 --> 00:42:10.002
And I think if that happens I will say that this,
My programme, has really reached its climax,

00:42:10.021 --> 00:42:13.332
because that’s one of the things
I wanted to know from you.

00:42:13.334 --> 00:42:17.828
That when we have that place done,

00:42:17.868 --> 00:42:21.548
I didn’t want to have it into cement and all that,

00:42:21.555 --> 00:42:29.952
to make cement houses and all, but I wanted to make it
into ethnic style of huts, but comfortable and clean.

00:42:29.982 --> 00:42:31.752
What do you say?

00:42:31.757 --> 00:42:34.257
Yes. Yes Mother.

00:42:41.907 --> 00:42:46.543
That’s good. Then that can be
done very easily, very soon.

00:42:46.568 --> 00:42:51.703
And we can start it this year, of course not, but
maybe next year we might start that kind of a school.

00:42:51.716 --> 00:42:56.603
We have already got teachers, we’ve got
everything and we’ve got land also.

00:42:56.636 --> 00:43:03.596
Can you imagine? And the land will be near some river
where you can jump into it every day, every minute.

00:43:09.787 --> 00:43:15.341
That would be nice near a river. We should have
a big place where you all can enjoy yourself.

00:43:15.341 --> 00:43:19.621
Anything else? Any other suggestion?

00:43:21.831 --> 00:43:23.201
Cooking classes.

00:43:23.201 --> 00:43:26.791
Yes, Indian cooking. We would
like to know Indian cooking.

00:43:26.813 --> 00:43:31.281
One of them is that. There are twenty-one crafts.

00:43:31.343 --> 00:43:36.093
Indian cooking, Indian sewing.

00:43:36.121 --> 00:43:42.673
Sewing also. Embroidery, then housekeeping.

00:43:51.665 --> 00:43:54.165
Husband management.

00:44:04.254 --> 00:44:08.565
How Indian women manage their husbands!

00:44:08.584 --> 00:44:11.084
Without arguing, without fighting.

00:44:11.084 --> 00:44:14.965
The husbands, just, you see,
never allow them to cook.

00:44:18.171 --> 00:44:22.405
No cooking will be allowed to be learned by men.

00:44:24.529 --> 00:44:32.340
So the women will know only the cooking and
men will have to come home to have their food.

00:44:41.881 --> 00:44:45.394
That’s how we manage our husbands.

00:44:45.431 --> 00:44:49.004
Best way to manage your husband is
through his stomach and tongue.

00:44:51.284 --> 00:44:54.625
Every man is a child as
far as this is concerned.

00:44:54.625 --> 00:44:57.125
Children marketing, Mother.

00:44:57.125 --> 00:45:01.944
Children. They are all children as
far as food is concerned, you see.

00:45:01.953 --> 00:45:07.328
So, if you know how to make Indian food, I tell you
there are so many permutations and combinations,

00:45:07.324 --> 00:45:12.014
that they look forward. You see, every day
you don’t have the same stuff in India.

00:45:12.034 --> 00:45:18.674
The repetition may come after two, three days or
maybe after two, three years if you are an expert cook.

00:45:18.727 --> 00:45:20.252
It’s like that.

00:45:22.078 --> 00:45:29.787
So… and decorations of the
house, everything we’ll have it.

00:45:29.811 --> 00:45:31.291
Like stone carving.

00:45:31.291 --> 00:45:39.651
Stone carving, wood carving, ivory
carving and there are other carving also.

00:45:39.651 --> 00:45:47.235
We have what you call, yes, this is a
silversmith, goldsmith, that is there.

00:45:47.235 --> 00:45:53.630
And also weaving, weaving of different types.

00:45:53.630 --> 00:45:58.635
What else? There are twenty-one,
we found out, which are very easy.

00:45:59.348 --> 00:46:00.578
What about painting?

00:46:00.578 --> 00:46:01.438
Aaaa?

00:46:01.448 --> 00:46:02.878
What about painting?

00:46:02.874 --> 00:46:04.308
Painting.

00:46:04.720 --> 00:46:08.928
In the village I think it’s called
Madhubani, if I’m pronouncing that correctly.

00:46:08.937 --> 00:46:10.333
I beg your pardon.

00:46:10.333 --> 00:46:19.987
Madhubani, I’ve read in a book about a village or area
in India where almost all of the women learn to paint.

00:46:19.987 --> 00:46:21.727
Oh, that’s in the north.

00:46:21.727 --> 00:46:25.953
Yes, I gave you paintings out of
that. You didn’t get the paintings?

00:46:25.974 --> 00:46:28.474
Those who got married, in their house, there?

00:46:28.474 --> 00:46:29.363
You have one?

00:46:29.363 --> 00:46:34.013
We have one, somewhere. You have given Daniel
one, I think. We have it, here. I’ll show them.

00:46:34.046 --> 00:46:40.073
Yes, I see. We have, the whole village
will be doing carving of the wood.

00:46:40.073 --> 00:46:42.433
Then one village will be doing the inlay work,

00:46:42.423 --> 00:46:44.923
one village will be doing painting work, like that.

00:46:44.923 --> 00:46:46.813
We can do that.

00:46:46.813 --> 00:46:51.663
That’s something very, very
remarkable that painting business.

00:46:52.966 --> 00:46:56.091
Not one village but quite many.

00:46:57.977 --> 00:46:59.301
Madhubani,

00:47:00.357 --> 00:47:08.203
Madhubani painting, yes. And then also
this, what you call knitting and cane work.

00:47:08.203 --> 00:47:10.517
Oh, beautiful!

00:47:10.517 --> 00:47:13.017
Canework,

00:47:13.017 --> 00:47:18.972
canework and making mattresses, chatais,
what you call, mats, and things like that.

00:47:19.015 --> 00:47:21.515
Canework; that all can do.

00:47:21.515 --> 00:47:30.017
inlay work, inlay work, inlay in wood, inlay
in under stone, inlay; all that you can learn.

00:47:30.737 --> 00:47:36.304
Could be many things, much many more like the,
you see, these things also we make very well,

00:47:36.304 --> 00:47:37.864
very decorative.

00:47:37.886 --> 00:47:40.984
Mandapas, we call them.
Extremely beautiful, they are.

00:47:40.984 --> 00:47:43.484
Very well done.

00:47:45.984 --> 00:47:48.484
Also many things we can learn it.

00:47:51.083 --> 00:47:58.143
Silver is very, very, nice, but in India they
don’t make silver utensils out of sheets.

00:47:58.163 --> 00:48:02.048
They make it out of, what you
call them, aaa....

00:48:03.785 --> 00:48:04.438
I don't know.

00:48:04.426 --> 00:48:06.228
moulded, moulded one.

00:48:06.246 --> 00:48:09.043
I’ll have the tea I think.
it has gone cold or not?

00:48:10.567 --> 00:48:12.400
It is moulded.

00:48:12.408 --> 00:48:13.740
And wax.

00:48:13.761 --> 00:48:14.743
Wax work?

00:48:14.743 --> 00:48:18.330
And in wax and then they melt it like for the casting.

00:48:18.354 --> 00:48:19.634
Casting.

00:48:19.634 --> 00:48:24.862
And also, they do wax work
on the saris and clothes.

00:48:26.412 --> 00:48:29.114
That’s very… what they are called? Batik.

00:48:30.422 --> 00:48:32.542
They do a batik also on the leather work.

00:48:32.515 --> 00:48:35.942
Leather work, batik, very
beautiful leather. Batik work.

00:48:35.942 --> 00:48:41.012
But only thing is when you will be there you will be
as it is that the American taste, as he’s saying.

00:48:41.047 --> 00:48:43.547
We’ll have something with the American taste.

00:48:43.547 --> 00:48:49.919
Then we are very good at doing certain
things which are very, very expensive here;

00:48:49.943 --> 00:48:59.418
is making frames out of
silver, gold, out of, er, horn.

00:48:59.449 --> 00:49:02.581
Horn, we are very good at horn carvings.

00:49:02.581 --> 00:49:05.872
Out of horn you can make
so many things in India

00:49:06.849 --> 00:49:09.349
And then this metal work,

00:49:09.349 --> 00:49:10.489
brass.

00:49:12.449 --> 00:49:14.949
All kinds of brass work. Glass work!

00:49:14.946 --> 00:49:20.186
We have tremendous glass and
our crockery also is very good now.

00:49:20.186 --> 00:49:24.176
Our crockery is now being exported to Russia.

00:49:24.201 --> 00:49:27.476
And also our crystal.

00:49:29.877 --> 00:49:35.920
Then we have, what you call, all kinds of
glass work; beautiful glass work we have.

00:49:36.928 --> 00:49:40.030
Beautiful animals and things
they make, beautiful.

00:49:42.047 --> 00:49:49.928
(Shri Mataji is shown something.)

00:49:50.964 --> 00:49:51.788
How did you get it?

00:49:51.788 --> 00:49:55.025
I don’t know. I just find
it somehow and it’s there.

00:49:57.906 --> 00:50:00.406
Yes, they are very different, aren’t they?

00:50:05.943 --> 00:50:08.583
She doesn’t want to leave you.

00:50:14.671 --> 00:50:15.661
Shanti.

00:50:15.673 --> 00:50:18.173
Is she still with Me or with You?

00:50:18.173 --> 00:50:20.673
Somewhere.

00:50:21.112 --> 00:50:22.302
Shanti.

00:50:28.452 --> 00:50:31.735
Then also we have our temples.

00:50:31.785 --> 00:50:34.885
How we make our temples, it’s
very interesting, you know.

00:50:34.885 --> 00:50:36.595
We remember that, its
stone carving, Mother.

00:50:36.628 --> 00:50:40.763
Stone carving. No,
that’s you carve stones.

00:50:40.783 --> 00:50:48.413
Then the carved stones are put in such a way that they, the complete pillar is made, you see, out of that.

00:50:48.443 --> 00:50:50.433
But that is also very big art.

00:50:50.453 --> 00:50:58.829
Sometimes the carved stones are such that you cannot make out whether it is one stone or there are many pieces.

00:50:58.849 --> 00:51:00.869
They are great.

00:51:01.929 --> 00:51:04.429
So we can learn so we can
make some temples here.

00:51:04.454 --> 00:51:08.099
Yes, you can, you can have.

00:51:08.132 --> 00:51:15.086
But what I would say that, it would be better that you, you learn it and tell them what do you want, you see.

00:51:15.086 --> 00:51:18.981
Like now we have lot of
carving, but say, Greek style.

00:51:18.981 --> 00:51:22.746
Or something, you have
four dimensional things.

00:51:22.751 --> 00:51:27.361
That they don’t do. You can tell them, “We
want four dimensional.” They can do it.

00:51:27.365 --> 00:51:30.741
Work it out on stone or marble,
anything you want to do.

00:51:32.046 --> 00:51:33.454
And toy making.

00:51:33.544 --> 00:51:34.674
What about mirror work?

00:51:34.685 --> 00:51:35.254
I beg your pardon.

00:51:35.254 --> 00:51:35.764
Mirror.

00:51:35.764 --> 00:51:39.284
Mirror work? Quite a lot. That’s
in embroidery and all that.

00:51:39.287 --> 00:51:40.017
And also...

00:51:40.017 --> 00:51:43.027
Oh Mother, I don’t know, elephant and
things we can hang on Christmas tree

00:51:43.027 --> 00:51:45.277
Yes, yes. That is, that is made there.

00:51:45.277 --> 00:51:48.487
That’s quite a lot; that’s
quite a lot you can do.

00:51:48.487 --> 00:51:53.300
Plus you see what they do, it is a mirror
work on the clothes and things like that,

00:51:53.335 --> 00:51:54.865
that also quite a lot.

00:51:54.865 --> 00:51:57.365
There is the whole country is
doing it;

00:51:58.425 --> 00:52:03.475
the whole country is. You won’t
know how, where to stop it.

00:52:07.090 --> 00:52:10.585
We make the beautiful
Ganapatis and all other things.

00:52:10.609 --> 00:52:15.680
Especially from Nagpur from where I
come, they make the best Ganapatis.

00:52:15.706 --> 00:52:23.084
There’s a kind of a... Now here this clay that
you use so expensive; in India is very cheap.

00:52:24.424 --> 00:52:26.764
Only thing we do not have proper firing.

00:52:26.764 --> 00:52:34.754
But we have crockery; we have got,
what you call that, er, porcelain,

00:52:34.791 --> 00:52:38.367
kind of a porcelain, beautiful.

00:52:38.391 --> 00:52:41.827
And we have ceramics; all
these three things we have.

00:52:41.832 --> 00:52:45.927
But they are to be properly understood
in Indian style. It’s very different.

00:52:45.962 --> 00:52:50.385
Like I went to Japan. I said, “I want
to, I’ve come to see some ceramics.”

00:52:50.415 --> 00:52:55.315
I went to one place where they were
making some ceramics with their hands.

00:52:55.346 --> 00:52:57.685
So they said, “Here they are all on leave.”

00:52:57.685 --> 00:53:02.915
I said, “Really? They are on holidays?” They said, “No, no, they have now gone to India to learn ceramics.”

00:53:02.938 --> 00:53:07.315
So I looked at them. I said,
“From where do you learn?”

00:53:07.324 --> 00:53:09.975
Then they told Me the place
from where they learn

00:53:10.014 --> 00:53:12.514
and that place is so close
to My husband’s place.

00:53:12.514 --> 00:53:15.706
When I went there I went to
see that, and it was there.

00:53:18.686 --> 00:53:24.636
Like that, so many, because, you see, we
haven’t got machinery so we, our hands work out.

00:53:24.636 --> 00:53:32.268
Kashmir work is, papier-mâché
work is so much, so much.

00:53:35.138 --> 00:53:39.510
There’s no end to it. Everything
they use it for making.

00:53:39.510 --> 00:53:42.838
They never allow any lines to go straight.

00:53:42.880 --> 00:53:45.990
It has to be worked out into something.

00:53:46.020 --> 00:53:49.446
Out of these also they make tent, tent things.

00:53:52.524 --> 00:53:56.376
But you see, that is how one should live
with the matter, to make it beautiful,

00:53:58.685 --> 00:54:01.415
and that can be brought
here for no money at all,

00:54:01.435 --> 00:54:06.875
quite cheaply, compared to these people are
making so much money and they have no taste also.

00:54:06.915 --> 00:54:14.455
But if you can get something like that, you can sell it for
a cheap price and people will have better taste to live.

00:54:14.475 --> 00:54:26.482
There I have been investigating it, the import
laws, and they are rather strict in this country.

00:54:26.482 --> 00:54:32.728
I’m not sure what they would consider, if they would consider things that are in pieces coming from another country

00:54:32.730 --> 00:54:35.878
(unclear)

00:54:35.920 --> 00:54:41.438
Certainly four things are heavily tariffed and controlled.

00:54:41.462 --> 00:54:43.962
So there is, export is high.

00:54:43.962 --> 00:54:48.833
(Unclear) If hand-made, is a labour by the
country which [unclear] no taxes at all.

00:54:48.833 --> 00:54:52.143
You see, if it is hand-made
in America, no problem.

00:54:52.153 --> 00:54:53.683
No tariff at all. True.

00:54:53.683 --> 00:54:56.893
You see, if it is hand-made, even
in England you’ll be surprised,

00:54:56.893 --> 00:55:01.815
such a conservative country.
If it is hand-made, nothing.

00:55:01.849 --> 00:55:05.455
You see, they want to enrich their country
because they don’t have hand-made things.

00:55:05.499 --> 00:55:08.815
Ha, for other things they do it.

00:55:08.839 --> 00:55:14.675
Not only that, but anything that is more than
hundred years it’s absolutely free of cost.

00:55:14.675 --> 00:55:17.945
Anything hand-made!

00:55:17.955 --> 00:55:21.586
You just find out; you’ll be amazed.

00:55:21.586 --> 00:55:25.046
Otherwise, you will have
no hand-made things here.

00:55:27.578 --> 00:55:30.078
We’ll be all moving in plastic bags.

00:55:33.998 --> 00:55:37.538
Horrible! Horrible picture!

00:55:37.538 --> 00:55:43.858
To change all that, to bring in Sahaja Yoga, we have
to have natural things, beautiful things around us.

00:55:43.858 --> 00:55:47.392
And it’s very simple to do,
to get all these things here.

00:55:47.392 --> 00:55:49.876
But also then their taste will develop.

00:55:49.875 --> 00:55:52.375
People will think more.
You see, you have brains,

00:55:52.375 --> 00:56:00.715
you have better aesthetics and you can suggest
better things which Indians may not have.

00:56:00.715 --> 00:56:03.215
But that you can suggest and get things;

00:56:03.215 --> 00:56:04.295
Knitted!

00:56:04.305 --> 00:56:11.344
Knitted, hand-knitted clothes, hand-knitted
shirts, hand-knitted things, you can get very well.

00:56:11.344 --> 00:56:16.024
Cotton, beautiful cotton!

00:56:16.048 --> 00:56:22.364
Now here you get very good cotton, but that cotton
is to be stitched into proper dresses and things.

00:56:22.394 --> 00:56:23.474
Children’s wear.

00:56:23.474 --> 00:56:26.384
Children’s wear? Oh, beautiful children!

00:56:26.428 --> 00:56:31.274
We have one lady, she’s making such
beautiful children’s wear, Mrs Nigham,

00:56:31.270 --> 00:56:36.820
but she says, “The market here is so
great that we don’t want to export it.”

00:56:39.316 --> 00:56:44.770
Just imagine. But now supposing, I mean, if
there are some people like you help her out,

00:56:44.774 --> 00:56:49.660
then she might give you something for export.
For she makes.... she says she has no time.

00:56:49.660 --> 00:56:51.676
Many people have stopped exporting.

00:56:51.707 --> 00:56:54.207
The market is so great in India itself.

00:56:55.527 --> 00:56:56.901
Handicrafts!

00:57:01.883 --> 00:57:05.121
And you can give lots of
suggestions, lots of suggestions.

00:57:05.121 --> 00:57:09.822
Like, say, now you have got this brass.

00:57:09.832 --> 00:57:11.722
Now, how to keep it shining all the time?

00:57:11.722 --> 00:57:15.152
You might be able to give
some suggestions also.

00:57:15.167 --> 00:57:17.812
We have lots of treatments, lots of
chemical treatments to make them shine

00:57:17.812 --> 00:57:20.312
Ha, that’s what we don’t have.

00:57:21.742 --> 00:57:25.113
Also, like, we don’t have
good buckles in India, say.

00:57:25.139 --> 00:57:29.213
Really, we don’t have. We don’t
have proper glues in India.

00:57:29.232 --> 00:57:36.122
And we don’t have zips. You should export your
zips from here and get a, get a purse instead.

00:57:37.869 --> 00:57:41.799
Yes, we don’t have. Many
things we don’t have there.

00:57:41.809 --> 00:57:48.699
Proper, what you call, today, this, Marie showed
Me something in which you can fix a picture.

00:57:48.705 --> 00:57:54.286
That’s such a nice, beautiful,
er, latch. We don’t have.

00:57:54.286 --> 00:57:57.505
In India we don’t have such nice latches.

00:58:01.756 --> 00:58:04.256
So many things!

00:58:04.256 --> 00:58:11.086
You can also export from here your taps, but I don’t
know; American taps are such that they don’t fit anywhere.

00:58:12.400 --> 00:58:14.900
Everything is so funny here.

00:58:14.900 --> 00:58:19.994
Your, er, this thing, electrical is hundred and ten.

00:58:20.015 --> 00:58:22.515
It doesn’t fit anywhere.

00:58:23.825 --> 00:58:26.325
Hundred and ten!

00:58:28.197 --> 00:58:32.070
Everything is like that. You can’t
buy anything electrical from here.

00:58:32.491 --> 00:58:34.991
Your television is  different.

00:58:34.991 --> 00:58:38.390
You cannot use the cameras that you use here.

00:58:40.571 --> 00:58:42.893
How is the videos?

00:58:42.891 --> 00:58:45.103
You cannot use for videos, you see.

00:58:45.103 --> 00:58:48.103
We cannot use your tape recorders.

00:58:48.109 --> 00:58:50.403
Nothing electrical we can use.

00:58:50.403 --> 00:58:51.883
So what a bulk is gone.

00:58:51.923 --> 00:58:54.423
See, what will you export?

00:58:54.423 --> 00:58:57.823
I mean, your government is seeing to
it that nothing should be exported.

00:59:02.688 --> 00:59:04.628
What will you export then?

00:59:04.645 --> 00:59:08.541
Electrical goods are out.
Now take another. Your cars:

00:59:08.558 --> 00:59:12.241
your cars are funny. Nobody wants it,
because one reason: they are too big.

00:59:15.452 --> 00:59:22.972
But [unclear] it started here. I don’t understand how the rest of the world got out of sync or we got out of sync.....

00:59:23.899 --> 00:59:26.749
That’s the thing with them
is, that’s the main thing.

00:59:26.773 --> 00:59:30.171
It is that they want to
do something different.

00:59:30.180 --> 00:59:32.431
Can I have My sweater please?

00:59:32.431 --> 00:59:35.821
They always want to do something different.

00:59:35.841 --> 00:59:42.899
And in doing so, they have alienated themselves,
separated themselves from the rest of the world.

00:59:44.209 --> 00:59:51.631
That’s the point is. They, they just
don’t want to do the way others can do.

00:59:54.421 --> 00:59:56.921
I mean, a simple thing like a sweater, you see.

00:59:56.921 --> 00:59:59.421
I wanted to buy one for My son-in-law.

00:59:59.421 --> 01:00:02.901
It’s all funny style. It’s
not one that he would wear.

01:00:02.902 --> 01:00:08.311
Whatever generally people wear, is not
available here. They were all English.

01:00:08.311 --> 01:00:13.038
Otherwise, with a neck like
that, with a collar like that.

01:00:13.035 --> 01:00:17.208
And the frocks you try to buy for your
children, they’ll have all funny things.

01:00:18.858 --> 01:00:21.833
All is funny things they make.

01:00:21.853 --> 01:00:24.353
I went to see the socks.

01:00:24.353 --> 01:00:27.783
Socks are colours like,

01:00:27.803 --> 01:00:30.303
what you call them,

01:00:30.303 --> 01:00:32.803
what colours, shocking pink!

01:00:32.803 --> 01:00:35.303
Now imagine Me wearing a shocking pink.

01:00:38.353 --> 01:00:44.996
Ha, then we went to buy, I mean it’s like
that, went to buy what you call them, goggles?

01:00:44.996 --> 01:00:48.633
The ladies’ goggles, all of them, are like
this. You’ll like a witch, you know.

01:00:48.648 --> 01:00:51.148
All of them having like this. This is ladies’.

01:00:51.148 --> 01:00:57.581
All of them had some sort of a white stuff or a golden
stuff or anything coming out up to this point.

01:00:58.551 --> 01:01:02.887
I mean, if you wear, it is for
the witches to wear like this.

01:01:02.917 --> 01:01:06.177
And no Indian woman would
wear a thing, I don’t know.

01:01:06.207 --> 01:01:07.977
What to buy? Then I didn’t buy.

01:01:07.977 --> 01:01:09.737
Same with the watches.

01:01:09.767 --> 01:01:12.877
Everything big problem,
you know. It’s odd-looking;

01:01:12.887 --> 01:01:15.387
nothing decent.

01:01:15.387 --> 01:01:19.207
It’s odd-looking. I mean, simple things like this.

01:01:19.207 --> 01:01:21.027
What is the....?

01:01:21.037 --> 01:01:26.018
Traditional style. The traditional styles you can’t
get. They import them from England and Switzerland.

01:01:26.018 --> 01:01:31.318
No, no, all right, I don’t say traditional it
should be, but something near decency, isn’t it?

01:01:31.318 --> 01:01:39.478
Now supposing you have a sweater like this. I mean,
you are not some king or someone to walk like that.

01:01:39.478 --> 01:01:41.978
It looks so funny, na?

01:01:42.898 --> 01:01:45.398
All funny looking, I mean to say.

01:01:47.680 --> 01:01:51.318
Mother, and they sell clothes that are
already worn out. So when you buy them

01:01:51.348 --> 01:01:52.568
Ha, with holes.

01:01:52.588 --> 01:01:53.258
Yes!

01:01:57.926 --> 01:02:00.426
It is I can’t understand.

01:02:13.665 --> 01:02:17.406
Anything that we found that was
really something, we can say,

01:02:17.401 --> 01:02:20.816
it’s traditional or something
that anybody can wear decently,

01:02:20.816 --> 01:02:25.336
was all English.  All English!

01:02:25.344 --> 01:02:29.256
Or Polish or anything else but American!

01:02:31.096 --> 01:02:37.529
Either the pants would be baggy or would be so
tight that once you wear it you cannot take it out.

01:02:48.779 --> 01:02:51.279
Very difficult.

01:02:51.899 --> 01:02:56.156
That’s why they have junks here. Nobody
can take it and nobody can purchase it.

01:03:05.019 --> 01:03:07.039
Same with jewellery, I must say.

01:03:07.039 --> 01:03:09.019
Jewellery is also quite odd, you know.

01:03:09.019 --> 01:03:13.979
In the ear such big, big things you
know, hang from here up to here.

01:03:14.009 --> 01:03:16.979
There are jewelleries also very funny and queer.

01:03:16.999 --> 01:03:21.609
The original jewellery they used to make
was beautiful but they stopped making it.

01:03:21.619 --> 01:03:24.269
They import all the stuff now.

01:03:27.536 --> 01:03:30.746
I don’t know what to say, but really I feel

01:03:30.759 --> 01:03:38.886
that people must come to some universal understanding
in this country which stands for universality.

01:03:38.896 --> 01:03:42.313
It’s, is the centre of collectivity.

01:03:44.363 --> 01:03:47.946
Then you go on seeing people also like that.

01:03:47.946 --> 01:03:52.484
They become very queer. There’s
no universality in them.

01:03:54.414 --> 01:03:56.796
Somebody will talk like this;
another will talk like that.

01:03:56.796 --> 01:03:59.576
Every time you have to adjust
your ears to every person.

01:04:01.468 --> 01:04:03.424
That’s not good.

01:04:03.424 --> 01:04:09.134
I mean, if you have to have rapport with the whole
world, you must have certain norms, isn’t it?

01:04:09.153 --> 01:04:14.154
And this country should create
norms. On the contrary, I would say.

01:04:35.424 --> 01:04:39.025
In these, I think twenty-five years or so,

01:04:39.039 --> 01:04:41.520
they have deviated so
much (teacup falls over)

01:04:41.545 --> 01:04:43.620
in individualism and all that. It’s too much.

01:04:43.620 --> 01:04:46.920
Now this is also a very
small cup, American style.

01:04:49.044 --> 01:04:50.310
It’s all right; doesn’t matter.

01:04:50.306 --> 01:04:54.687
Can you get something to clean?
It’s rather a small cup for a tea.

01:04:55.518 --> 01:04:57.597
It’s all right. You just bring some cloth.

01:04:57.597 --> 01:04:59.917
It’s all right. Doesn’t matter. Nothing to be worried

01:04:59.917 --> 01:05:02.967
So this is what happens.

01:05:02.967 --> 01:05:07.426
And one has to bring it to that normalcy.

01:05:08.817 --> 01:05:13.276
I don’t know when will be they think about it?

01:05:13.298 --> 01:05:18.908
It’s all right. That’s all right. We just only,
you have to use a little wet cloth for this,

01:05:18.908 --> 01:05:21.828
because the tea takes....,
the silk might get it.

01:05:21.838 --> 01:05:24.998
Just wet, wet it and little bit water.

01:05:30.698 --> 01:05:33.198
So,

01:05:33.198 --> 01:05:41.397
I would suggest that when you people try to do something,
like even having a video now, we had a problem.

01:05:41.397 --> 01:05:47.403
I said, please try to buy something
in which you’ll also have VHS,

01:05:47.436 --> 01:05:50.783
because now we can’t make for
Americans something separate.

01:05:50.783 --> 01:05:52.943
And you will be missing all the videos.

01:05:52.943 --> 01:05:54.663
We are, Mother.

01:05:54.663 --> 01:05:56.033
You are missing it.

01:05:56.033 --> 01:06:00.703
Now, to get one like that , it's
very cheap here in the market.

01:06:00.710 --> 01:06:05.091
because I know that it doesn’t cost. So
now if you have to buy any television,

01:06:05.091 --> 01:06:08.662
buy that one, which has got both the, isn’t it?

01:06:08.662 --> 01:06:12.231
I think this Doctor Bhaava has bought one.

01:06:13.687 --> 01:06:16.187
Aaaa?  (unclear). Yes!

01:06:16.187 --> 01:06:17.193
And it cost?

01:06:17.193 --> 01:06:20.683
Three, three hundred, three hundred dollars.

01:06:26.520 --> 01:06:27.944
Yeah!

01:06:27.949 --> 01:06:31.514
I mean, most of the recording
is done by this particular thing.

01:06:32.734 --> 01:06:36.751
So if you buy that now, I mean,
instead of buying anything else.

01:06:37.730 --> 01:06:41.771
Can you? No, is it, is it little bit wet?

01:06:41.767 --> 01:06:44.397
It should be wet.

01:06:44.397 --> 01:06:47.457
Yes, water. Little water on it; that’s all.

01:06:47.477 --> 01:06:49.977
Bring some water on it; that’s all.

01:06:49.977 --> 01:06:55.499
If you buy something like that, then wherever we have
the films, anywhere in the world,

01:06:55.525 --> 01:07:00.189
you can see it. Except for America, everybody can see it.

01:07:02.601 --> 01:07:05.171
A very big problem!

01:07:05.171 --> 01:07:10.761
And to adopt anything from this
one to yours is very difficult.

01:07:10.791 --> 01:07:14.161
But more difficult it is from yours to this.

01:07:15.098 --> 01:07:17.598
Is even more difficult!

01:07:33.787 --> 01:07:36.662
He’s so playful. Let him play,

01:07:36.662 --> 01:07:39.162
let him play.

01:07:50.672 --> 01:07:51.667
He’s feeling shy.

01:07:51.702 --> 01:07:54.202
He's hiding from us.

01:08:01.332 --> 01:08:03.832
Hello, Bhima, I can see you.

01:08:03.832 --> 01:08:06.332
Aaaaaa!

01:08:09.512 --> 01:08:12.650
Are, baba, so much problem.
Just, just a little wet cloth.

01:08:17.033 --> 01:08:22.807
It’s too much. Just have it wet cloth.
She's rubbing. She knows. Just a wee bit.

01:08:22.807 --> 01:08:23.877
Here it is wet.

01:08:23.877 --> 01:08:26.377
Yes, it’s all right. Anything will do.

01:08:26.377 --> 01:08:29.284
Just, just a wee bit it stands.

01:08:29.304 --> 01:08:32.687
It takes out the stain; that’s all.

01:08:32.687 --> 01:08:36.244
It’s a... you see, always there’s a stain with this.

01:08:36.247 --> 01:08:37.024
Clean, ha.

01:08:37.024 --> 01:08:42.857
A bigger cup would be better,
not such a small one.

01:08:42.889 --> 01:08:46.717
You see, normally they use that
small one for the coffee, isn’t it?

01:08:46.717 --> 01:08:49.217
North India, America, I don’t know.

01:08:52.937 --> 01:08:56.316
There, it’s faded, already.

01:09:03.836 --> 01:09:08.776
No, it is, it's there a little bit, already there.

01:09:09.746 --> 01:09:12.246
You can take it out there.

01:09:14.606 --> 01:09:16.217
The stain is there also.

01:09:16.217 --> 01:09:16.887
Aaaa?

01:09:16.887 --> 01:09:19.387
It is a half-cup, like a half-truth.

01:09:19.387 --> 01:09:24.117
But you don’t have it anywhere in
the world, one like that, you see.

01:09:24.117 --> 01:09:27.807
It’s for a coffee after dinner.

01:09:27.812 --> 01:09:29.277
That’s a wee bit.

01:09:29.277 --> 01:09:35.339
But for tea they don’t have it. But you see,
in America you have to accept everything.

01:09:43.586 --> 01:09:46.086
Does soap help?

01:09:46.086 --> 01:09:48.586
No, just water, cold water.

01:09:48.586 --> 01:09:51.086
Yes. Is done, I think.

01:09:51.116 --> 01:09:53.304
One little bit there.

01:09:53.306 --> 01:09:55.806
And a bit there.

01:09:55.806 --> 01:09:59.324
Yes, I think so. He is very good at taking.

01:09:59.327 --> 01:10:03.741
Oh, Danny is another, a real Englishman.

01:10:03.761 --> 01:10:05.741
He is so resourceful; you have no idea.

01:10:05.781 --> 01:10:09.481
Oh, he’s extremely resourceful.

01:10:15.329 --> 01:10:20.393
He is so resourceful man, I have to
come across another person like him.

01:10:20.401 --> 01:10:22.901
He’s like Jeeves, you know.

01:10:24.831 --> 01:10:28.348
Leave it to Jeeves; leave it to Jeeves.

01:10:30.051 --> 01:10:32.551
Extremely resourceful.

01:10:48.544 --> 01:10:51.044
Thank you.

01:10:55.919 --> 01:10:59.530
He’s very straightforward and very resourceful.

01:10:59.563 --> 01:11:00.964
(More tea is offered.)

01:11:00.974 --> 01:11:04.244
Ah, this is a proper cup.

01:11:20.294 --> 01:11:24.274
Ha, that’s it. That’s it, very sweet. Thank you.

01:11:28.924 --> 01:11:31.424
Very good, thank you.

01:11:35.284 --> 01:11:37.784
